        Description copied from interface: IStructureElement
        Try place the block by taking resource from given IItemSource.

        You might want to use StructureUtility.survivalPlaceBlock(Block, int, World, int, int, int, IItemSource, net.minecraft.entity.player.EntityPlayer) or its overloads to implement this.

        The default implementation provided will

        1. Get IStructureElement.BlocksToPlace via IStructureElement.getBlocksToPlace(Object, World, int, int, int, ItemStack, AutoPlaceEnvironment). If not null
          1. call IStructureElement.check(Object, World, int, int, int). If this returns true, IStructureElement.PlaceResult.SKIP will be returned without further action.
          2. Use the IStructureElement.BlocksToPlace retrieved earlier and passed in IItemSource to determine an item to place
          3. Hand over control to StructureUtility.survivalPlaceBlock(ItemStack, NBTMode, NBTTagCompound, boolean, World, int, int, int, IItemSource, EntityPlayer, Consumer)
        2. Call legacy IStructureElement.survivalPlaceBlock(Object, World, int, int, int, ItemStack, IItemSource, EntityPlayerMP, Consumer) if env.getActor() contains an EntityPlayerMP
        3. Emit warning under debug mode (or throw exception under panic mode), then return IStructureElement.PlaceResult.SKIP
        It should be noticed that the default implementation is likely to cause unexpected issues if the IStructureElement.check(Object, World, int, int, int) is not side effect free, or is not idempotent. E.g. the IStructureElement.check(Object, World, int, int, int) will add current coord to a List. As this method might be invoked at a location that is already accepted, this will cause the machine to have multiple of this coord in its list.
        Specified by:
        survivalPlaceBlock in interface IStructureElement<T>
        trigger - trigger item
        env - autoplacing environment
